[2] South Korea, 1 new case, 1 new death - MOH, 19 Jun 2015
Date: 19 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean Ministry of Health [in Korean, trans. by Korean subscribers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323585


MERS-CoV Case Update
- Total number of cases now stands at 166: 112 currently receiving treatment (67 percent), 30 discharged (18 percent), 24 dead (14 percent).
- Of the 112 receiving treatment: 96 in stable condition (86 percent), 16 reportedly unstable (14 percent).
- 1 additional case and 6 additional recoveries compared to previous day's numbers; 1 new fatality.
- 77 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 59 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 30 are of hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced 1 new case of MERS-CoV -- bringing the total tally up to 166 as of 6 AM KST, 19 Jun 2015.
- The number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 6 since yesterday [18 Jun 2015] and currently stands at 112 (67 percent of total); 6 have recovered, bringing the number up to 30 (18 percent); the fatality count has increased by 1, totaling at 24 (14 percent).

New Cases
- 1 additional case has been confirmed since yesterday
- Patient no. 166 (male, 62yo) came in contact with the virus while visiting an admitted family member at Samsung hospital.
- Following up on Patient no. 165 (male, 33yo), a new case reported on 18 Jun 2015:
- The patient was hospitalized at Kyung Hee University Medical Center from 6-13 Jun 2015 for dialysis treatment around the same time frame as Patient no. 76, who was hospitalized at the same hospital from 5-6 Jun 2015.

New Dischargees
- Patients no. 26 (43-year-old male), 32 (54-year-old male), 39 (62-year-old male), 57 (57-year-old male), 70 (59-year-old male), and 138 (37-year-old male) have been discharged on 18 Jun 2015, bringing the total number of recoveries to 30.
- Dischargees underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 30 total recoveries, 20 (67 percent) are male with 10 (33 percent) being female; 13 have been in their 40s (43 percent), 7 have been in their 50s (23 percent), 3 patients each have been in their 20s and 60s (10 percent each), with 2 patients each having been in their 30s and 70s (7 percent each).

New Fatalities
- Patient no. 120 (75-year-old male) was pronounced dead on the morning of 19 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 24.
- Of the 24 reported fatalities to date, 17 have been male (71 percent), while 7 have been female (29 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s and 70s with 8 (33 percent) fatalities each, followed by 4 (17 percent) fatalities in the 50s, 3 (13 percent) in the 80s, and 1 (4 percent) in the 40s.
- 22 of the 24 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD, cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 166 total cases reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 46 percent (77 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 36 percent of total cases (59), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is reported to be at 18 percent (30).
- Male infectees comprise 61 percent of the total cases (101), and females, 39 percent (65).
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 34 patients each (20 percent each) are in the 50s and 60s, 30 (18 percent) are in their 40s, 27 are in their 70s (16 percent), while 24 are in their 30s (14 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 18 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 5930 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 12 percent lower than previous day's numbers (a decrease of 799); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 5535, which equates to an increase of 1043 (or 23 percent) compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 5930 under quarantine, 5161 are under home isolation (a 12 percent decrease, or a decrease of 696), while the number of hospital quarantines has also decreased by 103 (12 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 769.

