[This article is an excellent step in the right direction contributing to our knowledge and understanding of MERS-CoV infections and when virus is detectable. Notable is the finding that "MERS-CoV RNA was detected over 8 days after fever onset, in serum samples, but only in the 1st 4 days in throat swabs. Sputum was collected and the result of the test was positive for MERS-CoV from Day 7 when pneumonia was detected. We tested 2 faecal samples and obtained positive results on Day 10 and 15."

Note that there were 5 days between the observation of cough and fever of the imported case and the documentation of hilar infiltrates on X-ray (evidence of pneumonia on chest X-ray) -- one wonders how many mild cases are missed because MERS-CoV is not thought of until the appearance of the pulmonary infiltrates?

